item.description:
Tags Probability  , Statistics    Statement of Theorem Stated mathematically as:
\begin{equation} P(A|B)=\frac{P(B|A)P(A)}{P(B)} \end{equation}
Where:
 P(A|B) is the probability of event A happening given that B is true P(B|A) is the probability of event B happening given that A is true P(A) and P(B) are the probabilities of observing A and B respectively A and B are different events  Proof \begin{align*} P(A|B) &amp;=\frac{P(A\cap B)}{P(B)} \\ P(B|A) &amp;=\frac{P(A\cap B)}{P(A)} \\ \therefore\quad P(A\cap B)&amp;=P(B|A)P(A) \\ P(A|B)&amp;=\frac{P(B|A)P(A)}{P(B)} \end{align*}
